{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521802"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:37:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13753"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.14,0.18,0.08,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65070"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50506"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1758"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"2543"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11863"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14191"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44833"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65070"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old Irish-Australian woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a recent diagnosis of bronchiectasis confirmed by high-resolution computed tomography. She reports a history of recurrent respiratory and gastrointestinal infections and a chronic productive cough since her early thirties. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has three children, all delivered vaginally without complications. She has maintained a normal body mass index throughout her life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 78/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Auscultation reveals bilateral coarse crackles at the lung bases. Investigations show a normal full blood count and a chest X-ray showing tram-track opacities consistent with bronchiectasis. Sputum microscopy, culture and sensitivity demonstrated oral flora with no concerning or resistant organisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to assess the aetiology of her bronchiectasis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-1 antitrypsin level","Bronchoscopy with lavage","Serum immunoglobulins","Aspergillus specific IgE","Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to investigate potential underlying causes in a patient with newly diagnosed bronchiectasis, especially any reversible or treatable conditions. Common aetiologies of bronchiectasis include post-infectious (e.g., after severe pneumonia, tuberculosis, or childhood infections), immunodeficiencies, cystic fibrosis, allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA), primary ciliary dyskinesia, and connective tissue disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum immunoglobulins\u003C/strong\u003E should be measured to assess for immunodeficiencies, a common cause of bronchiectasis. This test is particularly relevant given the patient\u0027s history of recurrent respiratory infections. Immunodeficiencies such as common variable immunodeficiency, IgA deficiency, and hyper-IgM syndrome can lead to recurrent infections and bronchiectasis. Immunodeficiency identification can guide further management and treatment, including potential immunoglobulin replacement therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with lavage\u003C/strong\u003E can help obtain samples for microbiological and cytological analysis in cases of recurrent infections. Still, it is not typically the first step in investigating the aetiology of bronchiectasis. It may be considered later if initial investigations are inconclusive or if there\u0027s suspicion of an endobronchial lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlpha-1 antitrypsin level\u003C/strong\u003E testing would be more appropriate in patients with early-onset emphysema, particularly those with lower lobe predominant disease. While alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency can cause bronchiectasis, this patient lacks other typical features such as early-onset emphysema or liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus-specific IgE testing \u003C/strong\u003Eis used to diagnose allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA), which can cause bronchiectasis. However, ABPA primarily occurs in patients with a history of asthma or cystic fibrosis. Patients will also often have elevated eosinophils, not seen in this case. Given that this patient does not have a history of these conditions, there is no acute indication to perform testing for ABPA as the first test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene testing\u003C/strong\u003E is more likely to be positive in younger patients or those with a suggestive history of cystic fibrosis. Of note she has had normal fertility, no malabsorption issues, maintained normal weight, and symptoms only started in adulthood. While cystic fibrosis can present later in life, it is less common in a 45-year-old without other suggestive symptoms. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther tests that can be considered to investigate the cause of bronchiectasis include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFull blood count - elevated platelets are a poor prognostic factor, eosinophils can suggest aetiologies such as ABPA or asthma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESweat test for cystic fibrosis - especially in young patients or those with other symptoms consistent with cystic fibrosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESputum culture and sensitivity - to determine respiratory flora and any known resistance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor and anti-CCP antibodies - to screen for rheumatoid arthritis-associated bronchiectasis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlpha-1 antitrypsin levels - especially in patients with early onset emphysema\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECiliary function tests - if primary ciliary dyskinesia is suspected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, given the history of recurrent infections, serum immunoglobulins are the most appropriate initial test to investigate the aetiology of bronchiectasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A comprehensive workup for bronchiectasis should include investigations for underlying causes such as immunodeficiencies, cystic fibrosis, and allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis.","Serum immunoglobulin testing is particularly important in patients with recurrent respiratory infections and bronchiectasis to rule out immunodeficiencies."],"references":["Shoemark A, Ozerovitch L, Wilson R. Aetiology in adult patients with bronchiectasis. Respiratory Medicine. 2007;101(6):1163-70. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0954611106005968","Tam JS, Routes JM. Common variable immunodeficiency. Am J Rhinol Allergy. 2013 Jul-Aug;27(4):260-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3901442/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50506"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50506"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T13:24:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T13:25:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65070"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","syno